reviewText: Buy it for that match after you by the Chris Benoit DVD(that has them at Rumble(2003)and Cage on Raw(2001).Angle V Benoit is so good, I watched it something like 10 times(it's that good)on the first day I bought this DVD. This is not like any TLC or hardcore match were big bumps take place because it has mat wrestling and german suplexes and so on, I'de watch this match any day over the trianguler ladder match that was rated "2nd best" match of Wrestle Mania history. There's  a good match between Rey and Chavo(at least 2.5 stars/5) on Sunday night heat on the extras then Eddie V Edge(solid).RVD V HHH is a good fight. RVD carried the match along mostly by him self.Summerslam 2002 is an event that all the matches are watcheble and Unforgiven has 4 watchable matches. If your choosing between the two and you haven't bought them yet and your a big fan of Kurt Angle or Chris Benoit buy this. Kurt Angle V Chris Benoit unforgiven is better than Kurt V Rey(Sum Slam 02)and alot better than Chris Benoit V RVD.edit: the Trish V Molly Holly is a good match if you give it a chance. They put in some effort, it's alot better than...The Smackdown main event for WWE title, Brock V Taker, this match is mostly a brawl with punches, one of them matches that drags on what seems like hours. Brock/Rock Summerslam is alot better(3.5 - 4 star match).

reviewText: When this ppv first happened, I thought it was aweful.  But I just bought it for some reason, thinking it would be good, and boy was it ever.  Here are the matches:Kane, Booker T, Goldust, and Bubba Ray Dudley vs. The Un-Americans.  This match was probably the worst on the DVD, but it was still pretty good.  A bit sloppy, but what would u expect, 8 man tags are always sloppy.  Booker T and all win with Kane nailing the Chokeslam.  **IC Title- Chris Jericho vs. Ric Flair.  This match was actually pretty good.  A few of Ric's old tricks were used by Jericho.  Jericho fakes a leg injury, and when Flair turns his back, Jericho shows he faked it and locks on the Walls of Jericho for the win.  ***Interpromotion Tag Team Match.  Billy & Chuck vs. Rosey & Jamal.  Pretty good match.  Billy and Chuck wrestled this match like it was their last match together(which it was but...).  After a good battle, Rosey and Jamal get the win.Edge vs. Eddie Guerrero.  Probably the 2nd best match of the night.  I think this was better than their Summerslam match.  These two really put on a great match together, and should work together more often.  Eddie gets the win thanks to a sunset flip off the second rope(after nailing Edge's head on the exposed post).  ****World Title- Triple H vs. Rob Van Dam.  This match was ok, nothing special in my view.  RVD doesnt take control til the very end.  Ric Flair shocks the world by nailing RVD with a sledgehammer, and helping HHH retain the title.  **Women's Title- Trish vs. Molly.  Pretty good, I think even better than the World Title match.  I never really cared about this fued, but they did a good job with their match.  Trish wins with the Stratusfaction.  **1/2Kurt Angle vs. Chris Benoit.  Stole the show, no questions asked.  I don't know how these guys do it, but just about every time they wrestle at a ppv, they steal the show, which makes me never get tired of these two men, heels or faces.  Benoit wins thanks to his foot on the ropes(aaawww!!). *****WWE Undisputed Title- Brock Lesner vs. Undertaker.  This fued was extremely personal.  I'm a huge Taker fan, and this was probably Taker's most personal fued from what I remember.  This match was just like ppl say: a brutal war.  These two beat the heck out of each other, unfortunately causing a double DQ.  But just to show how pissed off he was, before the show was over, Taker fought Brock up to the stage, and threw Brock right thru the Unforgiven set, and in my opinion, making Brock Lesner famous.  ***1/2Extras include 5 bonus interviews, Rey Mysterio vs. Chavo from Sunday Night Heat, Undertaker's Desire video, and promos of RVD and Chris Benoit.That is my opinion and review of this DVD.  If ya asked everyone, they'd probably say rent this first, but me, I'd say go ahead and buy it.

reviewText: This event was a very solid ppv with some excellent in ring action.  The show starts off with a surprisingly good 8-man tag match between the Un-Americans and Kane, Bubba, Booker T and Goldust. The second match was a decent match for the IC title in which Chris Jericho uses some tricks to win over Ric Flair. Edge vs. Eddie Guerrero was another great match between the up and coming superstars. A ... interpromotional match between Jamal and Rosie and Billy and Chuck followed. In the first main event, Triple H defended the World heavyweight Title against RVD in an excellent match with some shocking interference from the Nature Boy.  The womens title changed hands when Trish beat Molly. The match of the night was Angle vs Benoit.  This one might have been the match of the year. A mat classic. Undertaker vs Lesnar was a brutal match for the WWE title. A disappointing ending to most people but I loked the idea of fueling the rivalry with a non finish.
summary: Unforgiven was as good as should have been expected

reviewText: Bubba Ray Dudley, Booker T, Goldust, Kane vs. The Un-Americans - This started off fast with the babyfaces having some fun including Bubba & Goldust doing the Dusty elbow before the Un-Americans had to resort to cheating behind the referees back to gain the advantage.  It went back & forth between both teams resulting in a fun match.Intercontinental Champion Chris Jericho vs. Ric Flair - Jericho regained the I.C. title on the previous RAW while Flair suffered an upset loss to Rico causing Jericho to issue this SummerSlam rematch thinking that he had an advantage over Flair since he had better momentum this time around.  Chris was in control early with his moves like the springboard dropkick on the apron & missle dropkick in the ring but Flair made his comeback with chops & threw Jericho so hard into the corner that he flew to the outside.  However it really came down who was really the "dirtier player" in this game that resulted in the winner here & the loser suffering an embarrassing lose that would ammunition for what would happen later in the night.  This wasn't the quality of a month earlier at SummerSlam but more about finishing off this story in order to developing another one.Edge vs. Eddie Guerrero - Another SummerSlam rematch here as Edge came out very aggressive with moves like a powerslam & vertical suplex before Eddie focused on Edge's head with a tornado DDT from the second rope & a unique neck twist chinlock.  This match only picked up the intensity as Eddie would taunt Edge to hit him before throwing his own punches only for Edge to knock him out & mount a comeback that included a sick powerbomb, facedrop onto the turnbuckle off his shoulders, and Edgecution DDT.  This was a very hard fought match between both men who started off aggressive & didn't let up at all.[Edge: Decade Of Decadance]Billy & Chuck vs. 3 Minute Warning (Rosey & Jamal) - RAW vs. SmackDown match after 3MW interrupted the Billy & Chuck wedding a week earlier & attacked Stephanie McMahon in the process setting up this match with the stipulation that based off which brand's team won, Eric Bischoff would either have to kiss Steph's butt or Steph would have to perform "Hot Lesbian Action" (H.L.A.) later in the night while it should also be noted that Billy & Chuck's former stylist Rico was in 3MW's corner.  Rosey & Jamal were dominate as they singled out Chuck & kept him in the corner only for Chuck to make the hot tag to Billy after a miscalculation where Billy was able to counter an attempt as a samoan drop into a fameasser in mid-air before Rico would end up being the deciding factor in the match.  This was a good tag match for what it was but was only here to setup the story between Bischoff & Stephanie later in the night.World Champion Triple H vs. Rob Van Dam - Triple H tried to intimidate RVD only for RVD to respond with a slap & kept catching him in a side headlock & armdrags whenever Triple H tried to build some offense with RVD even mocking Triple H in regards to his pre-match water spit.  RVD continued to mount some offense only to crash & burn with a somersault dive onto the outside where Triple H finally took control throwing him into the steps before taking the match back into the ring working over RVD's neck with moves like the sleeper & neckbreaker while also using the ropes to choke before RVD fought back relying on his educated feet with various kicks & picked up the pace.  This was a real good match between both men but based off what happened backstage with Triple H & him calling out someone else for lacking the passion that he felt RVD did, this match was more about the beginning of a long alliance that would lead to an "Evolution" within the WWE.[History Of The World Heavyweight Championship]Womens Champion Molly Holly vs. Trish Stratus - This was pretty short & sweet as Trish was on the defense most of the match as Molly went after Trish with much aggression from pulling her hair to throwing Trish into steps & railing followed by doing a drop toehold on Trish sending her into the ropes throat first.  This was more of a Molly Holly showcase more than anything else in the short time they had.Chris Benoit vs. Kurt Angle - With both men being as competitive as they are, this started out exactly how you expected it to with a tie-up where both men didn't give it up to the point where it spilled to the outside before they went back into the ring & attempts submissions early on.  Benoit targeted Angle's shoulder went into the post twice with moves like the shoulderbreaker while Angle rebounded with 3 german suplexes before Benoit countered an AngleSlam with a suplex that flipped Angle inside out.  Both men were able to reverse each others submissions into their own while also having a unique variation like Angle applying the anklelock while he was trapped in Benoit's crossface.  This was the intense competitive wrestling match that you expected from these two based off their past & eventual future matches.WWE Champion Brock Lesnar vs. Undertaker - Taker was able to take Brock out of his game by constantly knocking him out of the ring frustrating him causing Heyman to cause a distraction for Brock to get an advantage only for Heyman himself to get a boot in the face for his troubles.  Brock worked over the midsection with shoulders in the corner & a grounded bearhug before Taker rebounded including a punch that caused Brock to lose his balance as the fight went to the outside with Brock causing Taker to bleed.  Referees started getting knocked out left & right while Taker took care of attempted interference by an ally of Brock & Heyman before Undertaker delivered the most brutal unprotected chairshot I've ever seen in my life that caused the seat of the chair to bend in half & Brock bleeding.  This match just got completely out of control causing the final referee to throw the match out but Taker would leave the lasting impression by throwing Brock through the Unforgiven set.  This was a teaser to setup the Hell In A Cell match for next month but Taker gave Brock more of a challenge than anyone did before him.(Bonus) Rey Mysterio vs. Chavo Guerrero - Chavo tried grounding Mysterio only for Rey to come back with lucha style armdrags & a baseball slide into a head scissors takedown on the floor before Chavo rebounded going after Rey's midsection became the target for Chavo as applied an abdominal stretch, knees to the gut, and a dropkick to the back while also using the ringpost.  This was a quick match but got the performance that you normally would expect from both men in this time.Other DVD extras include pre-show interviews with The Un-Americans & Ric Flair; post-match interviews with Kurt Angle, Chris Jericho, Booker T & Goldust; an Undertaker "Desire" music video; and vignettes for Rob Van Dam & Chris Benoit.This was the first PPV I ever saw live and man, it was a great show & looking back at it now...it still stands the test of time as one of the best WWE PPV's they've had since they split up RAW & SmackDown.  In the end, I highly recommend.
summary: One Of The Best PPV Since The Split

reviewText: Kane, Bubba Ray, Goldust, Booker T vs The Un-AmericansAfter a flurry of action that featured all eight men brawling with each other, Kane demolished Lance Storm with a chokeslam and got the pinfall!Winners: Kane, Bubba Ray, Goldust, Booker TAfter the match, Stephanie McMahon told Billy and Chuck backstage that they were going to beat Rosey & Jamal that night for the pride of SmackDown!, and not so Stephanie would avoid kissing another chick!Intercontinental ChampionshipChris Jericho vs Ric FlairChris Jericho defended his newly-won Intercontinental Championshipfor the first time, taking on 16-time World Champion and legend Ric Flair. Although the Nature Boy claims to be the dirtiest player in the game, it was Y2J pulling out the win after making use of an underhanded ploy. Jericho faked a knee injury, then popped to his feet and slipped Flair into the Walls of Jericho! The surprised referee called for the bell as Flair tapped out!Winner: Chris JerichoBackstage, Eric Bischoff told Rosey and Jamal that they are not just representing RAW, they're representing their RAW general manager as well. Rico came in and said that Rosey and Jamal are more than ready to take down Billy and Chuck.Eddie Guerrero vs EdgeIn a rematch of their outing at SummerSlam, Eddie Guerrero pinnedEdge after crashing him to the mat with a powerbomb delivered from the second rope. Eddie helped his cause by grabbing onto Edge's tights to make sure that he wouldn't kick out.Winner: Eddie GuerreroRosey & Jamal vs Billy & ChuckAfter an impressive, albeit hard fought, match, Rosey dropped Billywith a flying Samoan Drop and got the three count before Chuck could rush in for the save! Back in his office, Eric Bischoff gloated over the win by starting up the HLA chant with three lesbians standing nearby!Winners: Rosey & JamalWorld Heavyweight ChampionshipTriple H vs Rob Van DamRVD seemed to have the match wrapped up. Even though the refereewas out of commission, Mr. Pay-Per-View had momentum on his side. Things looked even brighter when Ric Flair raced into the ring and picked up a sledgehammer that The Game had dropped. Flair sneered and turned to Triple H, but suddenly whirled around and nailed RVD in the chest! Triple H gawked at Flair then cautiously set up Van Dam for the Pedigree! Flair helped the ref to his feet to count the 1-2-3! Flair and Triple H celebrated and left together with the World Heavyweight Championship in tow!Winner: Triple HWWE Women's ChampionshipTrish Stratus vs Molly HollyTrish countered some of Molly Holly's offense to hit the Stratusfaction,giving her a third reign with the WWE Women's Championship! Afterwards, Trish could barely express how much winning her third title meant to her.Winner and New WWE Women's Champion: Trish StratusBackstage, Rosey, Jamal, Rico and Eric Bischoff celebrated with several hot girls. Rico asked permission to go out and celebrated, and Bischoff told them all to go out on the town. However, The Bisch pulled two girls aside and told them they could help him out with some HLA later on!Chris Benoit vs Kurt AngleIn perhaps the most unpredictable match of the evening to thatpoint, Chris Benoit rolled up Kurt Angle and propped his feet up on the ropes for leverage to get the pinfall! Angle couldn't believe it, seeing as how he had Benoit wrapped up in the ankle lock just seconds before!Winner: Chris BenoitBrock Lesnar told Marc Loyd backstage that he's not sorry for intimidating the Undertaker's wife, and he had no problem with what he was going to do to the Undertaker that night!RAW General Manager Eric Bischoff strolled down to the ring with a lesbian on each arm. Stephanie McMahon soon joined them in the ring and Bischoff began by telling the lesbians to lose some of their restrictive clothing. Stephanie looked less than excited when the girls removed her jacket and gave her a full body massage. Just as the girls were about to get their HLA on, Bischoff stopped and sent the two lesbians backstage. Bischoff explained that he wanted this to be the most humiliating experience of her life. Bischoff brought out one ugly-looking, fat lady, who Stephanie immediately grabbed and began kissing! Without warning, the lesbian dropped Bischoff with a kick and tugged at her face! A plastic mask gave way to Rikishi's face! Seconds later, Bischoff found himself getting the longest Stink Face ever seen!The Undertaker vs Brock LesnarThe match between the Undertaker and Brock Lesnar was heated throughout. Both Superstars beat each other bloody and the match turned into an all-out brawl. When the referee tried to separate the two in the corner, Brock's anger took over as he pushed Taker away and pushed the ref into the corner to intimidate him. Unable to control the match, the ref had no choice but to call for the bell and rule the match a draw!DRAWBut that didn't stop Brock and Taker from finishing what they started earlier in the night. The Superstars traded more shots with each other and didn't finish until Dead Man Inc. tossed the Champion through the Unforgiven sign up on the stage!

reviewText: Unforgiven 2002 was actually a very good, underrated PPV.  It was the first PPV where both RAW and Smackdown had their own world champions.1. Kane, Booker T, Goldust, Bubba Ray Dudley vs. Christian, Lance Storm, William Regal, & Test (8 Man Tag Match)Great way to kick off the show.  The match marked the return of Kane to WWE PPV's for the first time since Wrestlemania 18.  Very entertaining high paced match.  Great finish, with almost all of the competitors completing their finishing move.  (8.5/10)2. Chris Jericho vs. Ric Flair (Intercontinental Title)Rematch of their Summerslam match.  The match is a little slow and disappointing, but is needed for what happens later in the show.  (6/10)3. Eddie Guerrero vs. EdgeAnother rematch of Summerslam.  It was a lot better than their Summerslam match.  Both men take some pretty heavy bumps in the match.  They work well together.  The two would go on to have an amazing No DQ, No Countout/Ladder match a few weeks later on Smackdown, but this match was great nonetheless.  (8.5/10)4. Rosey & Jamal vs. Billy & Chuck (Interpromotional Match)If Rosey & Jamal won, Stephanie McMahon would have to kiss a girl.  If Billy & Chuck won, Bischoff would have to kiss Steph's butt.  This was Rosey & Jamal's first match on a WWE PPV.  Very short, but good match.  (8/10)5. Triple H vs. Rob Van Dam (World Heavyweight Title)The two competitors worked well together and put on a very good match.  Contras of styles, but it went well.  Ric Flair makes a surprise appearance.  Good ending, but very shocking.  (8.5/10)6. Trish Stratus vs. Molly Holly (Women's Title)Nothing special here.  Who cares anyways.  (2/10)7. Chris Benoit vs. Kurt AngleAnother classic between these two.  Match of the night.  The crowd was really into it.  Great reversals, submission holds, suplexes, and near falls.  Everything that is expected when these two wrestle.  The ending is a little disappointing.  (9.5/10)8. Undertaker vs. Brock Lesnar (WWE Title)A lot of people were a little disappointed with the match, but I thought it was pretty good.  The two mixed well together.  Check out the chair shot Lesnar takes from Undertaker.  The ending is very disappointing, but is needed.  Good post match action.  (8/10)I would recommend picking up this DVD.  All of the matches are good except for Jericho/Flair and the women's match.  The Angle/Benoit match is worth the price of the DVD alone.Overall Rating:  8/10
summary: September 2002 -  Staples Center -  Los Angeles, CA

reviewText: Kane, Booker T, Goldust,  Bubba Ray Dudley vs. The UnAmericans (Test, Christian, Lance Storm, William Regal) - I didn't care much for this opening matches.  Tag matches with 8 men are seldom good as there is too much confusion and not enough time for wrestling.  This ended pretty much how one might expect with everyone hitting their finishers.  The match was one big mess.Intercontinental Title:  Chris Jericho (c) vs. Ric Flair - This was a much shorter match than I would have liked considering how good these two workers are.  Jericho is the perfect "heel", and the ending to this match was classic.Edge vs. Eddie Guerrero - Good match.  These two can really go, and this pairing makes for a very interesting match.  This would have been match of the night, if not for Angle/BenoitInterpromotional Match: Billy & Chuck vs. Jamal & Rosey - I thought this match was junk.  I've never cared for Jamal and Rosey or Billy and Chuck.  The two big men are not very impressive in the ring.  The gimmick for this match is that is the RAW team wins (Rosey and Jamal), Stephanie McMahon has to engage in some H.L.A. (Hot Lesbian Action).  If the Smackdown team wins (Billy and Chuck), Eric Bischoff has to kiss the butt of Stephanie.  The gimmick is the only reason this match wasn't completely pointless and uninteresting.World Title Match: Triple H (c) vs. Rob Van Dam - After Bischoff created the World Championship for RAW, he gave the belt to Triple H.  This is the first title defense of that gift of a belt.  It isn't until the end of the match that RVD gets any offense in, and by that point we don't really believe he can win.  Maybe it is just the pairing of the two wrestlers, but this wasn't that good of a match.Women's Title:  Molly Holly(c) vs. Trish Stratus - In a rematch from King of the Ring, this one falls short.  The KOTR match was much better.  This was what you would expect from a women's match.  The women's division has improved significantly, but you wouldn't be able to tell from this match.Kurt Angle vs. Chris Benoit - There is no question about it....this was the best match of the PPV!  I watch quite a bit of wrestling, and this is the best match I have seen in a long time.  This match featured quite a bit of chain wrestling with reversals, near falls and lots of action.  Benoit and Angle put on a wrestling clinic.  This match should go down as a classic, and had this been at a bigger PPV, it would be remembered for a long time.WWE Title:  Brock Lesnar (c) vs. Undertaker - How do you follow the Angle/Benoit classic?  With a brawl.  Despite Lesnar's amateur background, this was little more than a streetfight in the ring.  Some power moves, but mostly punching and kicking.  Not bad for what it was, but this is a forgettable match.  The ending was a major disappointment and a horrible way to end a PPV.  Had I been in the arena, I would have been booing just like the rest of the crowd.This was a slightly better than average PPV, but it is elevated by the greatness that was the Kurt Angle/Chris Benoit match.  It more than makes up for the main event, and redeems the entire program.
summary: Angle/Benoit is the reason to watch this!

reviewText: From winning the King of the Ring earlier in the year to becoming the youngest WWE Champion at SummerSlam & adding legends such as Hulk Hogan, Ric Flair & The Rock onto his winning list, Brock Lesnar faces his toughest test to date in the Undertaker.Kane, Booker T, Goldust & Bubba Ray Dudley vs The Un-Americans. This match got the show rolling as Kane's team was in control & even at times making fun of their opponents. The Canadian team were able to get some momentum back on their side & even begin to isolate their opponents before Kane was able to look dominate in his return match as this was just a fun & exciting opening match that the crowd really got into.Intercontinental Champion Chris Jericho vs Ric Flair. This was a SummerSlam rematch with the difference being that due to Jericho winning the title on the previous RAW that it was now a title match. Just like SummerSlam, Jericho had the advantage as he was in control punishing Flair while also getting cocky at times before Flair was able to return the favor with his signature chops including one that was so loud I even took a backseat to. However it was one man that was able to play against the rules very well that resulted in the result. I enjoyed their SummerSlam match more but this was a good match to watch.Edge vs Eddie Guerrero. Another rematch from SummerSlam with the difference being that Eddie had more crowd support here since they were in L.A. Edge started off in control with a powerslam & suplex while Eddie was able to comeback with a neckbreaker & tornado DDT from the corner buckle. Both men really picked it up from here with near falls with moves like a powerbomb, DDT, the electric chair drop before one man was able to use all his surroundings to get an edge (no pun intended). This topped their SummerSlam match but this match would be topped a few weeks later on SmackDown in their classic "No DQ" match.Inter-Promotional Match: Billy & Chuck vs 3 Minute Warning. This match had two stipulations in that if the RAW team would win, Stephanie McMahon would have to perform some HLA (Hot Lesbian Action) later on in the night while if the SmackDown team wins, then Eric Bischoff would have to kiss Stephanie's butt (who wouldn't want that job). Anyways this match also took a different turn when Rico had turned on his team of Billy & Chuck to join Rosey & Jamal. This was a good match overall as both teams used the strategy of singling out one member of the opposing team building towards the hot tag with the difference being Rosey & Jamal having the size & strength while Billy & Chuck had their experience as a team along with speed.World Heavyweight Champion Triple H vs Rob Van Dam. Van Dam started this match hot by out-wrestling Triple H with a series of armdrags with RVD even going as far as to mock to Triple H much to the crowd's delight. Triple H got more aggressive after that by responding with a slap to the face & taking advantage one high risk moves too many from RVD. Triple H attacked the neck of RVD while wearing him in the process before Van Dam would use his feet to regain momentum allowing both men to go back & forth  with a series of near falls before someone earlier in the night that Triple H had a confrontation with ended up being the deciding factor but not the way that everyone anticipated. This was a solid match between these two that made me wish they did more matches after rewatching this but this is memorable for starting the on-screen Triple H/Ric Flair duo.Womens Champion Molly Holly vs Trish Stratus. Molly took the fight to Trish right from the start being more aggressive than usual. Molly seemed to be in control of the match with Trish occassionally coming back before coming back to get the win. This was a short match overall but was good for what it was.Kurt Angle vs Chris Benoit. Anyone knows that each time you put these two men together, they are bound to steal the show. Both men were aggressive from the first tie up as they spilled out to the floor before trading submission holds back to back as soon as they returned to the ring. Benoit attacked the shoulder while using the ring post to his advantage whereas Angle applied a series of german suplexes that eventually resulted in Benoit delivering one of his own that had Angle flipped & land on his stomach & face as opposed to this back. The match got more intense as both men exchanged near falls with Angle delivering his trademark running belly to belly off the top rope whille Benoit connected with his diving headbutt before a series of counters from the anklelock to the crossface including both men applying their signature submissions to the other. Like I said earlier, these two together are usually bound to steal the show & in my opinion did so here.WWE Champion Brock Lesnar vs The Undertaker. This was Lesnar's first true test as champion but this one got personal over the past couple of weeks in regards to Undertaker's wife. You can feel the tension early from Taker shoving Lesnar during the staredown. Paul Heyman would get involved to give Brock an edge only to pay for it in the process but Brock was able to work the midsection of Taker with grounded holds, a bear hug & delivering shoulder blocks in the ribs. Taker was out to beat Lesnar up as he regained control with his strikes before Brock regained his control by busting Taker open. Taker got more aggressive from here as the match got out of control with referees being taken out, both men using a chair, Paul Heyman again getting involved, outside interference from Matt Hardy who had his own issues with Taker before Taker delivered a sickening chairshot to Lesnar that broke the chair around Lesnar's skull. However, Undertaker was not done as he let Lesnar know this wasn't over by tossing Brock through the Unforgiven set. This was to build towards their more memorable Hell In A Cell match a month later but out of their three match series (counting No Mercy '03), this was my second favorite match in their feud as it did come off as a fight more than a wrestling match.Overall, this was quite the show to follow up SummerSlam as most of the matches on here were good quality overall with storyline implications building up for future events so I'd recommend as it was one of the best from 2002.
summary: The Next Big Thing Enters The Yard

reviewText: I have to say that this was a great PPV, especially at the end where Eric Bischoff got the longest stinkface ever by Rikishi. Every match was pretty good in my opinion, except for the woman's championship match. Besides, there was no hype being built up for that match, all they did was make the match, and let Trish win. It sucked basically. Other than that, I LOVED the Kurt Angle vs. Chris Benoit match. A lot of different strategies and techniques used by each wrestler, and it was very entertaining every second you watched it. The WWE championship match was good, though it could've been a LOT better. I mean, come on. Matt Hardy interfeiring? That was dumb. And the referee had to stop the match because there was too much fighting going on? The referee should've been fired that night since it was so entertaining watching Undertaker and Brock Lesnar beat the hell outta each other. I have to say that when Taker threw Lesnar through the Unforgiven sign, THAT was awesome. Overall, nearly every match was good, and some matches had shockers, but overall, GREAT PPV!

reviewText: Unforgiven was a very good follow up to Summerslam a month earlier. The two world title matches weren't bad at all but the match that probably will be most remembered will be the meeting between Chris Benoit and Kurt Angle. They stole the show.1. Eight Man TagKane, Booker T, Goldust, & Buh Buh Ray Dudley vs. Test, Christian, Lance Storm, & William RegalThis was a good choice to open up the show. This really got the crowd going. Booker t had a good showing. Action was coming from everywhere once the match broke out. Pretty good ending as well. Good opener. 4/52. IC TitleChris Jericho vs. Ric FlairThis match really started out pretty good. But it wasn't as good as their summerslam encounter though. Some nice action in the ring and out with a little groundbased offense. Cheap tactics from Jericho was used which costed Flair the match. Not as good as their summerslam match but it's still worthy of checking out. 3.5/53. Eddie Guerrero vs. EdgeThis was another rematch from summerslam. Eddie used some interesting moves to wear down Edge. Eddie really focuses on the head and neck region of Edge here. A very nice second encounter from these two. Pretty good match up. 4/54. Billy & Chuck vs. 3 Minute Warning with RicoThis match was here to decide if Stephanie McMahon would engaged in with HLA later on in the ppv. The match went a little slow at times. Billy pulled off an impressive counter into the famea$$er on Jamal. Other than that nothing really special here. 3/55. World Heavyweight TitleTriple H vs. Rob Van DamThis was a really cool and nice match up from these two. I would have really liked to have seen this feud last a little bit longer than it did. RVD would mock HHH earlier in the match which would p-o hhh. RVD takes a nasty crash and burn dive over the top rope in trying to hit HHH. Triple h would then have the advantage for a little while. RVD got in some good counters. This match really exceeded my expectations. A very good title match from Raw. 4.5/56. Women's TitleTrish Stratus vs. Molly HollyA better than average match from the divas here. This was a very emotional match for Trish. A great win for Trish. 3.25/57. Chris Benoit vs. Kurt AngleBenoit & Angle does it again. I said it before and I'll say it again, these two put on another classic match. I have to say that Benoit and Angle were made for each other. No matter what the situation is, they always put on a great match for us. Benoit seemed that he was gettng the better of Angle here which frustrated Angle. A good groundbased match mixed in with some very good counters, finisher reversals, suplexes, and some brawling. A great all around match up. This is certainly match of the night. 5/5Hot Lesbian Action segment takes place here with the return of Rikishi.8. WWE TitleBrock Lesnar with Paul Heyman vs. UndertakerThis was a solid title match between Taker and Lesnar, too bad it was soon forgotten once their Hell in a Cell match took place a month later. This match was just a nasty brawl with some good slams and suplexes. Lesnar takes two of the hardest chair shots anyone has ever taken right here. The fans was really into this one too. The match ended in a brawl with the ref stopping the match once it got out of hands. A very personal vendetta for Taker. Another good title match but this doesn't even come close to their Hell in the Cell encounter at No mercy. 4.5/5Unforgiven had a couple of good matches. Nothing really bad on this card. Mostly continued a lot of feuds. This is a good ppv to check out sometime.
